<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dumbbell-Split-Squat">Dumbbell Split Squat</h3>



<p>If you like squats but want more unilateral movement, try the <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/dumbbell-split-squat" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">dumbbell split squat</a>. This compound movement targets the quadriceps, hamstrings, and glutes while engaging the hip flexors. Activating these muscle groups can help build strength and reduce <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10987311/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">back pain</a>, especially if weaknesses are noted.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Dumbbell split squats are excellent to incorporate with balance work. They decrease injury risk and <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5513080/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">improve performance</a>. From novice exercisers to elite athletes, anyone looking to improve stability will benefit from them.&nbsp;</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Dumbbell Split Squat" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/980489234?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dumbbell Split Squat Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Begin standing with feet shoulder-width apart. Hold a dumbbell in each hand, keeping shoulders down and back and chest open.</li>



<li>Take a large step forward with your right foot, keeping your torso upright. Your weight should be through the ball of your left foot and the entire right foot. Your hips should be neutral and forward.&nbsp;</li>



<li>With shoulder blades down and back, inhale and engage your core. Bend both knees, bringing the left knee down toward the floor. Your right thigh should be parallel to the floor.</li>



<li>Pause just above the ground. Exhale, squeeze your glutes and press firmly through your right foot to bring yourself to a standing position. Repeat as desired, then alternate legs.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Both knees should be at 90-degree angles when you’re at the bottom of the split squat.&nbsp;</li>



<li>If balance is an issue, ensure your feet are wide enough apart. Many people like to imagine walking on train tracks rather than a tightrope. This visual can help maintain the correct distance between your feet for balance.</li>



<li>Ensure you don’t slam your knee into the ground on the descent. Maintain control.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets &amp; Reps</h4>



<div class="wp-block-group medicine-table is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container">
